concept.description: The Arabidopsis thaliana cDNA of gene δ-OAT has been isolated based on sequence similarity with ornithine-δ-aminotransferase from yeast, mammal, plant and bacterial sequences. Its activity has not been directly tested although it is found in extract from Arabidopsis plants |CITS:[9576796]|.

The cDNA encoding arginase (EC 3.5.3.1) has been identified in Arabidopsis thaliana. Its molecular function of catalyzing the hydrolysis of L-arginine to form urea and L-ornithine has bee confirmed by functional complementation of an arginase-deficient yeast mutant. It has been suggested that the enzyme is involved in the mobilization of storage protein nitrogen |CITS:[7770544]|. The relationship of this urea cycle enzyme with the urea degradation has been demonstrated by the inhibition of urease which resulted in the accumulation of urea due to the metabolic activity of arginase |CITS:[7770520]|.

concept.description: The gene expression was repressed under dehydrate conditions, whereas induced after the plant was rehydrated.

The protein encoded by the Arabidopsis thaliana gene PDX2 was shown to have glutaminase activity |CITS:[17468224]|. Mutants defective in this gene are arrested at the globular stage of embryo development.

The cDNA encoding for ornithine carbamoyltransferase (OTC) has been identified from a T-DNA-taggedmutant. This mutant is sensitive to ornithine which accumulates due to a partial loss of function of the mutant allele of the OTC gene. The OTC gene overlaps with another, unrelated gene (AUL1), one of the rare cases of gene convergence observed in Arabidopsis thaliana |CITS: [10561504]|.
